04379nam a2200661Ia 9781501722141DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20181997nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017221417 a10.7591/97815017221412doi  a(DE-B1597)514916  a(OCoLC)1083589370  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDG571b.B444 1997eb 7aHIS0200002bisacsh04a306.2/0945/090412231 aBerezin, Mabel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking the Fascist Self :bThe Political Culture of Interwar Italy /cMabel Berezin. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b15 halftones; 1 map; 5 graphs; 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Wilder House series in politics, history, and culture00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tChronology -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Post-Fascism/Fascism: Italy I994/I922 -- t1. Interpreting Fascism/Explaining Ritual -- t2. Imagining a New Political Community: The Landscape of Ritual Action -- t3. Convergence and Commemoration: Reenacting the March on Rome -- t4. The Evolution of Ritual Genres: The March Continues -- t5. Colonizing Time: Rhythms of Fascist Ritual in Verona -- t6. Dead Bodies and Live Voices: Locating the Fascist Self -- tConclusion: Fascism/Identity /Ritual -- tMethodological Appendix -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn her examination of the culture of Italian fascism, Mabel Berezin focuses on how Mussolini's regime consciously constructed a nonliberal public sphere to support its political aims. Fascism stresses form over content, she believes, and the regime tried to build its political support through the careful construction and manipulation of public spectacles or rituals such as parades, commemoration ceremonies, and holiday festivities.The fascists believed they could rely on the motivating power of spectacle, and experiential symbols. In contrast with the liberal democratic notion of separable public and private selves, Italian fascism attempted to merge the public and private selves in political spectacles, creating communities of feeling in public piazzas. Such communities were only temporary, Berezin explains, and fascist identity was only formed to the extent that it could be articulated in a language of pre-existing cultural identities.In the Italian case, those identities meant the popular culture of Roman Catholicism and the cult of motherhood. Berezin hypothesizes that at particular historical moments certain social groups which perceive the division of public and private self as untenable on cultural grounds will gain political ascendance. Her hypothesis opens a new perspective on how fascism works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aFascism and culturezItalyxHistory. 0aFascismzItalyxHistory. 0aSymbolism in politicszItalyxHistory. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172214140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501722141423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501722141/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles